Facial Emotion Detection¶

Author: Evan Sims, 19 Oct 2023

Problem Definition¶

The context: Dozens of current and imagined human-computer interactions could be improved if the computer and successfully recognize human emotions by facial expression. Successful recognition of a users emotion could enable ther computer to adapt, take action, or detect a dangerous outcome, positive/negative experience, etc.
The objectives: Build and train a neural net that can be images of human faces and successfully recognize the emotion displayed (one of four in this case).
The key questions:

  1. How to load and pre-process data?
  2. What are the data like and how are they distributed?
  3. Why type of model is best and what level of complexity?
  4. How to augment the data and tune the hyperparameters to improve model performance?
  5. How do the models perform on test data?
  6. How to increase performance and speed up training?

The problem formulation: We are trying to build facial emotion recognition model, which is a type of computer vision. Fundamentally, it is a classification, in this case with four classes (happy, sad, surprise, and neutral).

About the dataset¶

The data set consists of 3 folders, i.e., 'test', 'train', and 'validation'. Each of these folders has four subfolders:

happy: Images of people who have happy facial expressions.
sad: Images of people with sad or upset facial expressions.
surprise: Images of people who have shocked or surprised facial expressions.
neutral: Images of people showing no prominent emotion in their facial expression at all.

# Check for any bad image:

folder = 'Facial_emotion_images/'
imgs_path = path + folder

for root, dirs, files in os.walk(imgs_path):
    for file in files:
        file_path = os.path.join(root, file)
        try:
            with Image.open(file_path) as img:
                img.verify()  # This checks if it's an actual image and can be opened
        except (IOError, SyntaxError) as e:
            print('Bad file:', file_path)

Observations on the data:

The dataset consists of tiny square grayscale images of peoples faces pre-labeled as either exhibiting the emotion of either happy, neutral, sad, or surprise (as indicated by their containing folder).

The images are 48x48 pixels, meaning our input layer will have 2304 neurons (grayscale) or 6912 (rgb). Likewise, our output layer will have four neurons, representing the four classes of the dataset (happy, neutral, sad, or surprise).

The dataset comprises a zipped file with the following architecture, where each sub-sub folder contains the actual .JPG image files:

Facial_emotion_images

  • test
    • happy
    • neutral
    • sad
    • surprise
  • train
    • happy
    • neutral
    • sad
    • surprise
  • validation
    • happy
    • neutral
    • sad
    • surprise

Visualizing our Classes¶

Let's look at our classes.

Write down your observation for each class. What do you think can be a unique feature of each emotion, that separates it from the remaining classes?

In [ ]:
def display_imgs(folder_path, num_imgs=10):

    img_files = [f for f in os.listdir(folder_path) if f.endswith('.jpg')]

    plt.figure(figsize=(15, num_imgs * 15))

    for i, image_file in enumerate(img_files[:num_imgs]):
        img_path = os.path.join(folder_path, image_file)
        img = Image.open(img_path)
        plt.subplot(1, num_imgs, i+1)
        plt.imshow(img, cmap='gray')
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

Observations and insights for all classes are provided at the end of the display sections as they are highly interrelated.

Observations and Insights:

In addition to the visualization here, it's fairly quick to manually inspect several hundred images from the classes to get a better feel for their character. A couple salient features are worth mentioning. While some images are aggressively cropped, in almost all cases the persons eyes and mouth are visible, which intuitively are the primary means by which human faces display emotion. One exception is that a few people are wearing sunglasses.

Some specifics on the individual emotions:

  • Happy: Happy faces are defined most clearly by the mouth, which is smiling or grinning and often displaying teeth. The eyes and eyebrows are in a variety of positions but are almost never deeply furrowed or downturned. There is significant engagement of the facial musculature.

  • Sad: Sad faces usually have downturned (ie frowning) or tightly pursed lips, eyes are often downturned and brows furrowed, but here there is a wide variety, too. Eyes are almost never widely open. Like happiness, the facial muscles are significantly engaged

  • Neutral: Neutral faces are ... neutral. The mouth and eyes are appear horizontal as compared the the other intense emotions. The mouth is closed or very slightly opened. The eyes are at an average degree of openness. The facial muscles are relaxed.

  • Surprise: Surprise is clearly defined by wide open or "O" shaped mouth and wide open eyes, often with hands on the mouth or cheeks.

The cohort that these images represent spans a wide array of races and ages, from infants to elderly. It even includes an image of George W Bush with a look of surprise. So we can hypothesize that a good generalizable deep learning model could work for images of people anywhere in the world and of any age, including former politicians.

We can also attempt to anticipate some difficulties that a model may have learning from these images. Many of the happy faces could be confused for surprised ones and vice versa. Likewise with neutral and sad. Many of the "neutral" faces also contain a wide variety of distinctively non-neutral expressions, such as boredom, frustration, sleepiness, weariness, and others. So we should bear these facts in mind when it comes to classification results and their limitations.

Checking Distribution of Classes¶

train_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/train'

classes = ['happy', 'sad', 'neutral', 'surprise']

class_counts = {}

for cls in classes:
    cls_path = os.path.join(train_path, cls)
    class_counts[cls] = len([f for f in os.listdir(cls_path) if f.endswith('.jpg')])

labels = list(class_counts.keys())
counts = list(class_counts.values())

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.bar(labels, counts)
plt.xlabel('Classes')
plt.ylabel('Number of Images')
plt.title('Distribution of Classes Among Training Data')
plt.show()


val_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/validation'

classes = ['happy', 'sad', 'neutral', 'surprise']

class_counts = {}

for cls in classes:
    cls_path = os.path.join(val_path, cls)
    class_counts[cls] = len([f for f in os.listdir(cls_path) if f.endswith('.jpg')])

Observations and Insights:

For the training data, there is a fairly even distribution among all classes. There's a bit fewer images showing surprise but likely not enough to matter.

For the validation data, there is an overrepresentation of happy and dearth of surprise. Based on how training and test results have gone, it doesn't seem to be a big enough difference to matter.

Creating our Data Loaders¶

In this section, we are creating data loaders that we will use as inputs to our Neural Network.

You have two options for the color_mode. You can set it to color_mode = 'rgb' or color_mode = 'grayscale'. You will need to try out both and see for yourself which one gives better performance.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.utils import shuffle
batch_size  = 32
img_size = 48 # height and width the same. Change to 224x224 for Transfer Learning models later.

train_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/train'
validation_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/validation'
test_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/test'

train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1./255,
    brightness_range=(0.,2.),
    shear_range=0.25,
    horizontal_flip=True,
)

validation_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1. / 255)

# Load images as both grayscale and rbg

color_mode = 'grayscale'

train_data_g = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train_path,
    target_size=(img_size, img_size),
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode=color_mode
)

validation_data_g = validation_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    validation_path,
    target_size=(img_size, img_size),
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode=color_mode
)

test_data_g = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
     test_path,
     target_size=(img_size, img_size),
     batch_size=batch_size,
     class_mode='categorical',
     color_mode=color_mode,
     shuffle=False
)


color_mode = 'rgb'

train_data_rgb = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train_path,
    target_size=(img_size, img_size),
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode=color_mode
)

validation_data_rgb = validation_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    validation_path,
    target_size=(img_size, img_size),
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode=color_mode
)

test_data_rgb = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
     test_path,
     target_size=(img_size, img_size),
     batch_size=batch_size,
     class_mode='categorical',
     color_mode=color_mode,
     shuffle=False
)

Functions for Reused Code¶

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def training_performance_plots(model_name, history):

    #model_name (str)
    if type(history) == dict:
      acc = history['accuracy']
      val_acc = history['val_accuracy']
      loss = history['loss']
      val_loss = history['val_loss']

    else:
      acc = history.history['accuracy']
      val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']
      loss = history.history['loss']
      val_loss = history.history['val_loss']

    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 6))
    fig.suptitle(f"Model Training Performance: {model_name}")

    ax1.plot(range(1, len(acc) + 1), acc)
    ax1.plot(range(1, len(val_acc) + 1), val_acc)
    ax1.set_title('History of Accuracy')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Epochs')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Accuracy')
    ax1.legend(['training', 'validation'])

    ax2.plot(range(1, len(loss) + 1), loss)
    ax2.plot(range(1, len(val_loss) + 1), val_loss)
    ax2.set_title('History of Loss')
    ax2.set_xlabel('Epochs')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Loss')
    ax2.legend(['training', 'validation'])

    plt.show()


def predict_and_report(model, test_data):

  predict = model.predict(test_data, steps=test_data.samples/test_data.batch_size)

  predict_labels = np.argmax(predict, axis = 1)

  y_test = test_data.classes

  accuracy = np.sum(predict_labels == y_test) / len(y_test)

  print(f"Test accuracy: {accuracy}")

  report = classification_report(y_test, predict_labels, target_names=test_data.class_indices.keys())
  print('\nClassification Report:\n')
  print(report)

  print('\nConfusion Matrix:')

  cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, predict_labels)

  plt.figure(figsize=(5, 4))
  sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues',
              xticklabels=test_data.class_indices,
              yticklabels=test_data.class_indices)
  plt.ylabel('True label')
  plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
  plt.show()

Model Building¶

Think About It:

  • Are Convolutional Neural Networks the right approach? Should we have gone with Artificial Neural Networks instead?
  • What are the advantages of CNNs over ANNs and are they applicable here?

Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) are a specialized class of neural net that are meant for processing images or other data with a grid-like structure. They are considered the state of the art for image recognition.

As key feature of CNNs is that neurons in the convolution layer are connected to only a small subset of neurons in the input layer, allowing the model to detect local patterns. For this and other reasons, and the fact CNNs are well established to be superior for image recognition make the choice a simple one.

Creating the Base Neural Network¶

In [ ]:
# Usual preliminaries:

backend.clear_session()
seed = 10
np.random.seed(seed)
random.seed(seed)
tf_random.set_seed(seed)
In [ ]:
model1_g = Sequential()

model1_g.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(2, 2), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(48, 48, 1)))  # Final value for input share =1 signifies grayscale
model1_g.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model1_g.add(Dropout(0.2))

model1_g.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(2, 2), activation='relu', padding='same'))
model1_g.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model1_g.add(Dropout(0.2))

model1_g.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(2, 2), activation='relu', padding='same'))
model1_g.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model1_g.add(Dropout(0.2))

model1_g.add(Flatten())
model1_g.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model1_g.add(Dropout(0.4))
model1_g.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))

model1_g.summary()

Compiling and Training the Model¶

In [ ]:
model1_g.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("model1_g.h5",
                             monitor='val_acc',
                             mode='max',
                             save_best_only=True,
                             verbose=1)

# EarlyStopping
earlystop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',
                          min_delta=0,
                          patience=3,
                          verbose=1,
                          restore_best_weights=True)

# ReduceLROnPlateau
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss',
                              factor=0.2,
                              patience=3,
                              verbose=1,
                              min_delta=0.0001)

callbacks = [checkpoint, earlystop, reduce_lr]

history_1g = model1_g.fit(
    train_data_g,
    epochs=20,
    validation_data=validation_data_g,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

Test accuracy: 0.625

Classification Report:

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

       happy       0.68      0.72      0.70        32
     neutral       0.52      0.69      0.59        32
         sad       0.38      0.31      0.34        32
    surprise       0.96      0.78      0.86        32

    accuracy                           0.62       128
   macro avg       0.64      0.62      0.62       128
weighted avg       0.64      0.62      0.62       128


Confusion Matrix:

Observations and Insights:

The model achieved a 0.6391 training accuracy and test accuracy: 0.7266. Not amazing as we would hope to approach 0.90.

The model does about equally well predicting happy, neutral, and surprised faces based on recall (~0.8) or accuracy. However, fully 31% of sad faces are predicted as neutral. This matches one of our predictions when manually inspecting the images before model building and training.

Creating the second Convolutional Neural Network¶

  • Try out a slightly larger architecture
In [ ]:
backend.clear_session()
seed = 10
np.random.seed(seed)
random.seed(seed)
tf_random.set_seed(seed)
In [ ]:
model2_g = Sequential()

model2_g.add(Conv2D(256, kernel_size=2, padding='same', input_shape=(48, 48, 1)))  # grayscale images
model2_g.add(BatchNormalization())
model2_g.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
model2_g.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))

model2_g.add(Conv2D(128, kernel_size=2, padding='same'))
model2_g.add(BatchNormalization())
model2_g.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
model2_g.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))

model2_g.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=2, padding='same'))
model2_g.add(BatchNormalization())
model2_g.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
model2_g.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))

model2_g.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=2, padding='same'))
model2_g.add(BatchNormalization())
model2_g.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
model2_g.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))

model2_g.add(Flatten())
model2_g.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model2_g.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model2_g.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))

model2_g.summary()

Compiling and Training the Model¶

In [ ]:
model2_g.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("model2_g.h5",
                             monitor='val_acc',
                             mode='max',
                             save_best_only=True,
                             verbose=1)

# EarlyStopping
earlystop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',
                          min_delta=0,
                          patience=3,
                          verbose=1,
                          restore_best_weights=True)

# ReduceLROnPlateau
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss',
                              factor=0.2,
                              patience=3,
                              verbose=1,
                              min_delta=0.0001)

callbacks = [checkpoint, earlystop, reduce_lr]
In [ ]:
history_2g = model2_g.fit(
    train_data_g,
    epochs=20,
    validation_data=validation_data_g,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

Creating the second Convolutional Neural Network using RGB Input¶

model2_rgb = Sequential()

model2_rgb.add(Conv2D(256, kernel_size=2, padding='same', input_shape=(48, 48, 3)))  # rgb images
model2_rgb.add(BatchNormalization())
model2_rgb.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
model2_rgb.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))

model2_rgb.add(Conv2D(128, kernel_size=2, padding='same'))
model2_rgb.add(BatchNormalization())
model2_rgb.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
model2_rgb.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))

model2_rgb.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=2, padding='same'))
model2_rgb.add(BatchNormalization())
model2_rgb.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
model2_rgb.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))

model2_rgb.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=2, padding='same'))
model2_rgb.add(BatchNormalization())
model2_rgb.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
model2_rgb.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))

model2_rgb.add(Flatten())
model2_rgb.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model2_rgb.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model2_rgb.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))

Think About It:¶

  • Did the models have a satisfactory performance? If not, then what are the possible reasons?
  • Which Color mode showed better overall performance? What are the possible reasons? Do you think having 'rgb' color mode is needed because the images are already black and white?

Transfer Learning Architectures¶

In this section, we will create several Transfer Learning architectures. For the pre-trained models, we will select three popular architectures namely, VGG16, ResNet v2, and Efficient Net. The difference between these architectures and the previous architectures is that these will require 3 input channels while the earlier ones worked on 'grayscale' images. Therefore, we need to create new DataLoaders.

Creating our Data Loaders for Transfer Learning Architectures¶

In this section, we are creating data loaders that we will use as inputs to our Neural Network. We will have to go with color_mode = 'rgb' as this is the required format for the transfer learning architectures.

In [ ]:
backend.clear_session()
seed = 20
np.random.seed(seed)
random.seed(seed)
tf_random.set_seed(seed)
In [ ]:
# Increased most augmentation ranges and added brightness, v flip, and channel shift

from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
from tensorflow.keras.applications.vgg16 import preprocess_input

taget_size = (224, 224) # Use image size on which VGG16 was originally trained, especially since we'll be training the base model layers
batch_size = 32

train_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/train'
validation_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/validation'
test_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/test'

# Data augmentation for training data
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    preprocessing_function=preprocess_input,
    rotation_range=5,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    #zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    vertical_flip=True,
    brightness_range=[0.8, 1.2],
    channel_shift_range=0.2,
    fill_mode='nearest'
)

val_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(preprocessing_function=preprocess_input)

test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(preprocessing_function=preprocess_input)


train_data = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train_path,
    target_size=taget_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode='rgb'
)

val_data = val_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    validation_path,
    target_size=taget_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode='rgb'
)

test_data = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    test_path,
    target_size=taget_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode='rgb',
    shuffle=False
)

Model Building¶

  • Import VGG16 upto the layer of your choice and add Fully Connected layers on top of it.
In [ ]:
# Import VGG16 up to the block5_pool layer
vgg.trainable = False

x = vgg.get_layer('block5_pool').output
x = Flatten()(x)
x = Dense(256, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)

predictions = Dense(4, activation='softmax')(x)

model_vgg16_custom = Model(inputs=vgg.input, outputs=predictions)

model_vgg16_custom.summary()

Compiling and Training the VGG16 Model¶

In [ ]:
model_vgg16_custom.compile(optimizer=AdamW(learning_rate=0.001),
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])


checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("model_vgg16_custom.h5",
                             monitor='val_acc',
                             mode='max',
                             save_best_only=True,
                             verbose=1)

earlystop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',
                          min_delta=0,
                          patience=4,
                          verbose=1,
                          restore_best_weights=True)

reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss',
                              factor=0.2,
                              patience=3,
                              verbose=1,
                              min_delta=0.00001)

callbacks = [checkpoint, earlystop, reduce_lr]
In [ ]:
# Implement training with gradual unfreezing of layers on the base model, 1 block at a time:

epochs = 4

overall_history_vgg = {
    'accuracy': [],
    'loss': [],
    'val_accuracy': [],
    'val_loss': []
}

## Training Block 1 ##
history_vgg = model_vgg16_custom.fit(
    train_data,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

for key in overall_history_vgg.keys():
    overall_history_vgg[key].extend(history_vgg.history[key])


## Training Block 2 ##

# Unlock Layers and Recompile mMdel:
for layer in vgg.layers[-4:]:
    layer.trainable=True

model_vgg16_custom.compile(optimizer=AdamW(learning_rate=0.0001),
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])

history_vgg = model_vgg16_custom.fit(
    train_data,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

for key in overall_history_vgg.keys():
    overall_history_vgg[key].extend(history_vgg.history[key])


## Training Block 3 ##

# Unlock Layers and Recompile mMdel:
for layer in vgg.layers[-8:]:
    layer.trainable=True

model_vgg16_custom.compile(optimizer=AdamW(learning_rate=0.0001),
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])

history_vgg = model_vgg16_custom.fit(
    train_data,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

for key in overall_history_vgg.keys():

                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])

history_vgg = model_vgg16_custom.fit(
    train_data,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

Think About It:

  • What do you infer from the general trend in the training performance?
  • Is the training accuracy consistently improving?
  • Is the validation accuracy also improving similarly?

Observations and Insights:

The custom VGG model achieved the best performance of all models tested, with an accuracy of 0.84 and f1-score of 0.85 on test data. Happy and Surprise performance is excellent - nearly 95%. Confusion persists on neutral and sad, probably reflecting poor training data labeling.

Note: You can even go back and build your own architecture on top of the VGG16 Transfer layer and see if you can improve the performance

ResNet V2 Model¶

In [ ]:
backend.clear_session()
seed = 84
np.random.seed(seed)
random.seed(seed)
tf_random.set_seed(seed)
In [ ]:
# Increased most augmentation ranges and added brightness, v flip, and channel shift

from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
from tensorflow.keras.applications.resnet_v2 import preprocess_input # must use the model specific preprocessing function.


taget_size = (224, 224) # Use image size on which VGG16 was originally trained, especially since we'll be training the base model layers
batch_size = 32

train_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/train'
validation_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/validation'
test_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/test'

# Data augmentation for training data
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    preprocessing_function=preprocess_input,
    rotation_range=5,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    #zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    vertical_flip=True,
    brightness_range=[0.8, 1.2],
    channel_shift_range=0.2,
    fill_mode='nearest'
)

val_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(preprocessing_function=preprocess_input)

test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(preprocessing_function=preprocess_input)


train_data = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train_path,
    target_size=taget_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode='rgb'
)

val_data = val_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    validation_path,
    target_size=taget_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode='rgb'
)

test_data = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    test_path,
    target_size=taget_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode='rgb',
    shuffle=False
)

Found 15109 images belonging to 4 classes.
Found 4977 images belonging to 4 classes.
Found 128 images belonging to 4 classes.

Model Building¶

  • Import Resnet v2 upto the layer of your choice and add Fully Connected layers on top of it.

Compiling and Training the Model¶

In [ ]:
rn_custom.compile(optimizer=AdamW(learning_rate=0.00001),
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])


checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("rn_custom.h5",
                             monitor='val_acc',
                             mode='max',
                             save_best_only=True,
                             verbose=1)

earlystop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',
                          min_delta=0,
                          patience=4,
                          verbose=1,
                          restore_best_weights=True)

reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss',
                              factor=0.2,
                              patience=3,
                              verbose=1,
                              min_delta=0.00001)

callbacks = [checkpoint, earlystop, reduce_lr]
In [ ]:
# Implement training with gradual unfreezing of layers on the base model, 1 block at a time:

epochs = 4

overall_history_rn = {
    'accuracy': [],
    'loss': [],
    'val_accuracy': [],
    'val_loss': []
}

## Training Block 1 ##
history_rn = rn_custom.fit(
    train_data,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

for key in overall_history_rn.keys():
    overall_history_rn[key].extend(history_rn.history[key])


## Training Block 2 ##

# Unlock Layers and Recompile Model:
for layer in rn.layers[-4:]:
    layer.trainable=True

rn_custom.compile(optimizer=AdamW(learning_rate=0.0001),
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])

history_rn = rn_custom.fit(
    train_data,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

for key in overall_history_rn.keys():
    overall_history_rn[key].extend(history_rn.history[key])


## Training Block 3 ##

# Unlock Layers and Recompile Model:
for layer in rn.layers[-8:]:
    layer.trainable=True

rn_custom.compile(optimizer=AdamW(learning_rate=0.0001),
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])

history_rn = rn_custom.fit(
    train_data,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

for key in overall_history_rn.keys():
    overall_history_rn[key].extend(history_rn.history[key])


## Training Block 4 ##

# Unlock Layers and Recompile Model:
for layer in rn.layers[-12:]:
    layer.trainable=True

rn_custom.compile(optimizer=AdamW(learning_rate=0.0001),
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])

history_rn = rn_custom.fit(
    train_data,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

for key in overall_history_rn.keys():
    overall_history_rn[key].extend(history_rn.history[key])


## Training Block 5 ##

# Unlock Layers and Recompile Model:
for layer in rn.layers[-12:]:
    layer.trainable=True

rn_custom.compile(optimizer=AdamW(learning_rate=0.0001),
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])

    train_data,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

    overall_history_rn[key].extend(history_rn.history[key])


## Training Block 6 ##

# Unlock Layers and Recompile Model:
for layer in rn.layers[-15:]:
    layer.trainable=True

rn_custom.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.00005),
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])

history_rn = rn_custom.fit(
    train_data,
    epochs=8,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

for key in overall_history_rn.keys():
    overall_history_rn[key].extend(history_rn.history[key])


## Training Block 7 ##

# Unlock Layers and Recompile Model:
for layer in rn.layers[:]:
    layer.trainable=True

rn_custom.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.00001), # when using 0.0001, model began overfitting in this block, but prob better ways to mitigate overfitting if a big problem
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])

history_rn = rn_custom.fit(
    train_data,
    epochs=epochs,
    validation_data=val_data,
    callbacks=callbacks
)

    File "/usr/local/lib/python3.10/dist-packages/keras/src/utils/traceback_utils.py", line 96, in error_handler
      return fn(*args, **kwargs)
    File "/usr/local/lib/python3.10/dist-packages/keras/src/layers/core/dense.py", line 241, in call

Matrix size-incompatible: In[0]: [32,8192], In[1]: [100352,256]

Observations and Insights:

ResNet was successfully trained to val_accuracy: 0.7693 but was unable to evaluate test data. It seems there's a matrix multiplication error somewhere but I was not able to resolve.

In [ ]:
# Increased most augmentation ranges and added brightness, v flip, and channel shift

from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
from tensorflow.keras.applications.efficientnet import preprocess_input # must use the model specific preprocessing function.


taget_size = (224, 224) # Use image size on which VGG16 was originally trained, especially since we'll be training the base model layers
batch_size = 32

train_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/train'
validation_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/validation'
test_path = path + 'Facial_emotion_images/test'

# Data augmentation for training data
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    preprocessing_function=preprocess_input,
    rotation_range=5,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    #zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    vertical_flip=True,
    brightness_range=[0.8, 1.2],
    channel_shift_range=0.2,
    fill_mode='nearest'
)

val_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(preprocessing_function=preprocess_input)

test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(preprocessing_function=preprocess_input)


train_data = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train_path,
    target_size=taget_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode='rgb'
)

val_data = val_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    validation_path,
    target_size=taget_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode='rgb'
)

test_data = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    test_path,
    target_size=taget_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    color_mode='rgb',
    shuffle=False
)

Model Building¶

  • Import EfficientNet upto the layer of your choice and add Fully Connected layers on top of it.
In [ ]:
EfficientNet.trainable = False

base_model = EfficientNetB0(include_top=False, weights='imagenet', input_shape=(224, 224, 3))
model_output = base_model.get_layer('block6e_expand_activation').output

x = Flatten()(model_output)
x = Dense(512, activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
predictions = Dense(4, activation='softmax')(x)

model = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=predictions)

Compiling and Training the Model¶

In [ ]:
efficient_custom.compile(optimizer=AdamW(learning_rate=0.00001),
                           loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                           metrics=['accuracy'])


checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("efficient_custom.h5",
                             monitor='val_acc',
                             mode='max',
                             save_best_only=True,
                             verbose=1)

earlystop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',
                          min_delta=0,
                          patience=4,
                          verbose=1,
                          restore_best_weights=True)

reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss',
                              factor=0.2,
                              patience=3,
                              verbose=1,
                              min_delta=0.00001)

callbacks = [checkpoint, earlystop, reduce_lr]

    epochs=20,
    validation_data=validation_data_rgb,
    validation_steps=validation_data_rgb.samples // batch_size,
    callbacks=callbacks

Evaluating the EfficientnetNet Model¶

Observations and Insights:

My EfficientNet model crashed and burned. I was unable to troubleshoot the issue. It seems there's a mismatch in one or more input/output shape compatibilitiy given the "Matrix size-incompatible" error but I couldn't figure out how to correct it.

Note: You can even go back and build your own architecture on top of the VGG16 Transfer layer and see if you can improve the performance.

Think About It:

  • What is your overall performance of these Transfer Learning Architectures? Can we draw a comparison of these models' performances. Are we satisfied with the accuracies that we have received?
  • Do you think our issue lies with 'rgb' color_mode?

Now that we have tried multiple pre-trained models, let's build a complex CNN architecture and see if we can get better performance.

Building a Complex Neural Network Architecture¶

In this section, we will build a more complex Convolutional Neural Network Model that has close to as many parameters as we had in our Transfer Learning Models. However, we will have only 1 input channel for our input images.

Creating our Data Loaders¶

In this section, we are creating data loaders which we will use as inputs to the more Complicated Convolutional Neural Network. We will go ahead with color_mode = 'grayscale'.

In [ ]:
backend.clear_session()
seed = 25
np.random.seed(seed)
random.seed(seed)
tf_random.set_seed(seed)

Model Building¶

  • Try building a layer with 5 Convolutional Blocks and see if performance increases.
In [ ]:
input_shape = (48, 48, 1)
inputs = Input(shape=input_shape)

x = Conv2D(64, kernel_size=2, padding='same', activation='relu')(inputs)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1)(x)
x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

x = Conv2D(128, kernel_size=2, padding='same', activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1)(x)
x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

x = Conv2D(512, kernel_size=2, padding='same', activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1)(x)
x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

x = Conv2D(512, kernel_size=2, padding='same', activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1)(x)
x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

x = Conv2D(128, kernel_size=2, padding='same', activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1)(x)
x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

x = Flatten()(x)
x = Dense(256)(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1)(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)

x = Dense(512)(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1)(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)

predictions = Dense(4, activation='softmax')(x)

model_cnn3 = Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=predictions)

model_cnn3.summary()

model_cnn3.compile(optimizer=custom_optimizer,
                   loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                   metrics=['accuracy'])

checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("model_EfficientNet_custom.h5",
                             monitor='val_acc',
                             mode='max',
                             save_best_only=True,
                             verbose=1)

earlystop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',
                          min_delta=0,
                          patience=5,
                          verbose=1,
                          restore_best_weights=True)

reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss',
                              factor=0.2,
                              patience=4,
                              verbose=1,
                              min_delta=0.00001)

callbacks = [checkpoint, earlystop, reduce_lr]

    epochs=50,
    validation_data=validation_data_g,
    validation_steps=validation_data_g.samples // batch_size,
    callbacks=callbacks

Plotting the Confusion Matrix for the chosen final model¶

In [ ]:
predict = model_cnn3.predict(test_data_g, steps=test_data_g.samples/test_data_g.batch_size)

predict_labels = np.argmax(predict, axis = 1)

y_test = test_data_g.classes

accuracy = np.sum(predict_labels == y_test) / len(y_test)
print(f"Test accuracy: {accuracy}")

report = classification_report(y_test, predict_labels, target_names=test_data_g.class_indices.keys())

print(report)

cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, predict_labels)

plt.figure(figsize=(5, 4))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues',
            xticklabels=test_data_g.class_indices,
            yticklabels=test_data_g.class_indices)
plt.ylabel('True label')
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.show()

Observations and Insights:

Conclusion:¶

Insights¶

Refined insights:¶

  • Many of images are hard to classify "correctly" by the human eye, so perhaps the quality of the dataset defines a ceiling for performance is below 0.9. After succeeding with the VGG model, we see almost 95% f1-score with happy and surprise but confusion persists with neutral and sad.

Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance:¶

  • UPDATE: VGG with gradual unlocking is the best model with an avg f1-score of 0.85 on test data.
  • The 3rd CNN with five convolution blocks performs the best, achieving a test accuracy of 0.766. The test f1-score for surprise is 0.90 so is performing quite well for that class. Happy is also close at 0.85. However, there is deep confusion between sad an neutral. What makes be believe this model is actually performing quite well is that when I inspected 100s of these images manually, I also am deeping confused about many of the sad and neutral images, so perhaps the quality of the dataset is not high enough to successfully train beyond these restults.

  • On the CNNs and other models, I tried a large variety of different hyperparameters values and data augmentation but these didn't help much and mostly stuck with standard values.

  • Using the A100 GPU was critical to speeding up training by ~10x. It would have been impossible to test a wide variety of models without this.

Proposal for the final solution design:¶

  • Adopt the custom VGG model.
  • Consider troubleshooting and fixing the resnet model.
